<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Executive trading</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic problem =
is that, if you are a senior executive at a public company, you always know=
 stuff about your company that the public doesn=E2=80=99t know, but you mig=
ht want to sell stock sometimes. The main reason that you might want to sel=
l stock is that=C2=A0you are compensated largely in stock and you need to t=
urn that stock into money to pay for houses, college tuition, outside busin=
ess ventures, etc. That seems fine. It is good for executives to be paid la=
rgely in stock (it aligns incentives), it is good for executives to be able=
 to live in houses and send their kids to college, and so you need some mec=
hanism to turn the stock into money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anothe=
r reason you might want to sell stock is that you think to yourself =E2=80=
=9Cthe price of my company=E2=80=99s stock is high, and it should not be, s=
o I will sell it before the price goes down.=E2=80=9D This is sort of an aw=
kward reason to sell stock, and you will not generally see executives say t=
his sort of thing. Still it is not technically illegal, on its own.=C2=A0If=
 you think that the public has all the relevant information about your comp=
any and nonetheless overvalues the stock, I suppose you are free to sell on=
 valuation concerns. It definitely happens, usually quietly, though=C2=A0El=
on Musk occasionally says that Tesla Inc. stock is overpriced and then sell=
s stock on Tesla=E2=80=99s behalf (though not generally from his personal a=
ccount).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third reason you might want to s=
ell is that, in the course of your job as a senior executive, you have lear=
ned some bad news about your company and would like to sell your stock befo=
re that news becomes public and the stock price goes down. This is bad! You=
 are definitely not allowed to do this, it is =E2=80=9Cinsider trading,=E2=
=80=9D you can go to prison.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the point =
is that the bad one exists on a continuum with the other ones. In the cours=
e of your job you are=C2=A0<em>always=C2=A0</em>learning things about your =
company. Some of those things are bad, or potentially bad; some of them mig=
ht make the stock go down, though it may not be obvious to you which those =
are. If you learn 100 things about your company in a day, and only 20 of th=
em are public, and then you sell some stock to pay college tuition, and the=
n the other 80 become public and the stock goes down, did you break the law=
?=C2=A0It is illegal to trade =E2=80=9Con the basis of material nonpublic i=
nformation,=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24212271.263782/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xMGI1LTE/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBa859194c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">rules</a> say that this means it=E2=80=99s illegal to trade if=
 you are =E2=80=9Caware of=E2=80=9D the information.=C2=A0If you knew secre=
t bad news, it is no defense to say =E2=80=9Cbut that=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<e=
m>why=C2=A0</em>I sold.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Public com=
panies and their executives have developed two basic ways of dealing with t=
his problem. One is the 10b5-1 plan: That same <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24212271.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbG=
wuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xMGI1LTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCa859194c" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">SEC rule</a>=
 says that you can set up an automatic plan when you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0</em>have any material nonpublic information, and then that plan can =
automatically sell stock for you even if you later come into possession of =
information. So you write a plan saying =E2=80=9Cin five years I=E2=80=99m =
gonna need to pay for college, so my broker will=C2=A0sell 500 shares on th=
e first day of each=C2=A0month for 48 months starting in five years.=E2=80=
=9D And then you forget about it, and in five years maybe you are working o=
n a merger or have bad earnings news or whatever, but it doesn=E2=80=99t ma=
tter because the plan is automatically selling stock without your involveme=
nt. These plans can be gamed a bit, and there are controversies around that=
 gaming and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/242122=
71.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtM=
DYtMDgvbW92aWVwYXNzLWNoYW5nZWQtc29tZS1wYXNzd29yZHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bf378fa4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> proposals to tighten the rule</a>, but the basic idea makes sense. If you=
 make a decision to sell far enough in advance, it=E2=80=99s unlikely that =
you=E2=80=99re trading on any inside information.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The other way to deal with the problem is: You do all your trading r=
ight after earnings. A company does stuff for three months, it makes money,=
 it spends a few weeks getting its books in order and then, a month or so a=
fter the quarter ends, it puts out a press release reporting how much money=
 it made that quarter. The press release =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the related SEC=
 filing, the Form 10-Q =E2=80=94=C2=A0contains=C2=A0detailed financial info=
rmation about how the company did, and qualitative updates on its business,=
 and often some guidance on its future earnings. The company does a call wi=
th analysts in which they ask questions about the quarter and the company=
=E2=80=99s executives do their best to explain how they see the world.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After all of that, the theory goes, the public =
knows as much about the company as its executives do. And so the next day =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0or maybe a few days later, to give the market time to ponder=
 all this news =E2=80=94=C2=A0the executives can go sell stock, on the theo=
ry that they don=E2=80=99t have any material nonpublic information that has=
n=E2=80=99t been disclosed to the public. They have an =E2=80=9Copen window=
=E2=80=9D to sell stock. Meanwhile they are like a month or two into the ne=
xt (three-month) quarter. Pretty soon they will start to know how=C2=A0<em>=
that=C2=A0</em>quarter is going, in rather more detail than the public does=
. And then they will have material nonpublic information and the window wil=
l close again.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So most public companies wil=
l have =E2=80=9Copen windows=E2=80=9D that start around the earnings announ=
cement for one quarter and run until sometime near the end of the next quar=
ter, and =E2=80=9Cblackout periods=E2=80=9D that start near the end of the =
quarter and run until around the earnings announcement, and executives are =
allowed to trade during open windows and not during blackout periods. I am =
being vague because this is vague. Some companies start their open windows =
with the earnings announcement; others wait a few days. Some companies star=
t their blackouts at the end of the quarter; others start them weeks earlie=
r.[1] There is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/242=
12271.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDEyLzEwLzE1L3NlY3=
VyaXRpZXMtb2ZmZXJpbmdzLWR1cmluZy1ibGFja291dC1wZXJpb2RzLWFuZC1mb2xsb3dpbmctY=
S1xdWFydGVyLWVuZC8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc12fcdc3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">no particular law</a> about any=
 of this; it is just some rules of thumb evolved by lawyers and companies t=
o allow executives to sell stock without getting in too much trouble.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And it has no real legal effect. If you se=
ll stock during a blackout period, you have broken a corporate rule and you=
r company really ought to fire you, but you have not necessarily broken the=
 law. And if you sell stock during an open window, but you have material no=
npublic information =E2=80=94=C2=A0say, a week after you announce earnings,=
 you learn of a big data breach etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you <em>have</em> =
broken the law. And there is no requirement that companies have blackout pe=
riods at all; a company could just say =E2=80=9Chey, try not to trade when =
you have material nonpublic information, but use your best judgment about w=
hen that is.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All that said, =
if you are a senior executive at a public company and:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">You sell 99.3% of your company stock after a quarter e=
nds but before the earnings announcement, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">the stock goes down 13.8% on the day after the earnings announc=
ement,</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">then people are going to write=
 mean articles about you and you are going to deserve it! From <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24212271.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9sb3Jkc3Rvd24tbW90b3JzLWV4ZWN1dGl2ZXMtc29sZC1zdG9ja=
y1haGVhZC1vZi1yZXBvcnRpbmctcmVzdWx0cy1hbmQtYmVmb3JlLXRyb3VibGVzLWNhbWUtdG8t=
bGlnaHQtMTE2MjQyNzMzODA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3063e231" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Wall Street Journal</a=
>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Several top executives at Lo=
rdstown Motors Corp.=C2=A0sold off chunks of stock in the electric-truck st=
artup ahead of reporting financial results, according to regulatory filings=
 disclosing the transactions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Securities la=
wyers and accountants say such trades raise questions about the company=E2=
=80=99s internal controls, especially in light of its recent troubles.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In all, five top executives, including the comp=
any=E2=80=99s president and its former chief financial officer, sold more t=
han $8 million in stock over three days in early February, according to the=
 filings. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of its executives, Chuan =
=E2=80=9CJohn=E2=80=9D Vo, who oversees Lordstown Motors=E2=80=99 propulsio=
n division, sold almost all of his vested equity=E2=80=9499.3%=E2=80=94on F=
eb. 2, leaving him with 717 shares and proceeds of more than $2.5 million, =
the filings show. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Securities lawy=
ers, accountants and analysts say such transactions are highly unusual, par=
ticularly because they occurred during a period when many other publicly tr=
aded companies bar executives from selling shares.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe wouldn=E2=80=99t expect insiders to typically sell at t=
hat time in the quarter,=E2=80=9D said Max Magee, an analyst at InsiderScor=
e, a research service that provides executive-trading data to investors to =
help guide investment decisions.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But the timing was good:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 early February trades by the five executives all occurred when the stock w=
as trading at more than $24 a share, company filings show. Similarly, they =
were executed as news was beginning to spread that a prototype of its first=
 electric-truck model caught fire 10 minutes into a road test in mid-Januar=
y.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lordstown=E2=80=99s fourth =
quarter ended on Dec. 31, 2020. The stock =E2=80=9Cpeaked in mid-February a=
t about $30.75 a share.=E2=80=9D The company=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24212271.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3NTk1NDYvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDM3NjkwL3RtMjExMDAyMm=
QxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB449cb0b6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">announced earnings</a> on March =
17, 2021; the stock was down 13.8% the next day, closing at $13.01. It clos=
ed at $10.65 last Friday. The Lordstown news has not been, uh,=C2=A0overwhe=
lmingly<em>=C2=A0</em>positive; this month it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/24212271.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnR=
pY2xlcy9sb3Jkc3Rvd24tbW90b3JzLWFtZW5kcy1hbm51YWwtZmlsaW5nLXdpdGgtZ29pbmctY2=
9uY2Vybi1ub3RpY2UtMTE2MjMxODE0MTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93693f6c" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">amended its annu=
al report for 2020</a> to say that it might not have enough cash to continu=
e as a going concern. If you were to argue that Lordstown=E2=80=99s senior =
executives knew things in February that the market did not know, and that t=
hose things were bad, and that when the market did eventually learn those t=
hings the stock went down =E2=80=94=C2=A0I feel like you would have a good =
case?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also this is not quite the poin=
t:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On June 14, the company said=
 a special committee formed by Lordstown Motors=E2=80=99 board had looked i=
nto the executives=E2=80=99 stock sales and concluded they =E2=80=9Cwere ma=
de for reasons unrelated to the performance of the company.=E2=80=9D</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24212271.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbnZlc3Rvci5sb3Jkc3=
Rvd25tb3RvcnMuY29tL25ld3MtcmVsZWFzZXMvbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlLWRldGFpbHMvbG9yZHN0b=
3duLW1vdG9ycy1yZXBvcnRzLXJlc3VsdHMtc3BlY2lhbC1jb21taXR0ZWUtaW52ZXN0aWdhdGlv=
bg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbdc67111" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;">that report</a>, which is=C2=A0<em>mainly=C2=A0=
</em>about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2421227=
1.263782/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMD=
YtMTUvbG9yZHN0b3duLXMtZWxlY3RyaWMtdHJ1Y2stb3JkZXJzLXdlcmUtdmFndWU/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB298973f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> yet another Lordstown scandal</a> (executives talked up pr=
e-orders =E2=80=9Cthat appear too vague or infirm to be appropriately inclu=
ded in the total number of pre-orders disclosed=E2=80=9D), but does mention=
 that executives dumped=C2=A0shares =E2=80=9Cfor reasons unrelated to the p=
erformance of the company or viability of the Endurance=E2=80=9D truck.[2] =
For instance,=C2=A0Lordstown=E2=80=99s president =E2=80=9Cused some of the =
proceeds to expand another venture that he had started recently, a turkey-h=
unting farm in Tennessee, a company spokesman said=E2=80=9D; he sold stock =
(at more than twice today=E2=80=99s price) not because he had doubts about =
